description.value: Mould-made pottery lamp in the form of the hull of a ship, with a row of ten wick-holes on each side. At the prow is a voluted nozzle, decorated between the volutes with a Dionysiac head and the head of a thyrsos. Within a triangular area on top near the stern are relief figures of Sarapis and Isis. Within the deck area are two relief groups: above is one of the Dioskouroi holding his horse and a spear; below is one of the Kabeiroi, a grotesque bearded dwarf-like figure holding a crucible and approaching a metal-working furnace. Between the two groups is a tabella ansata impressed with the Greek epithet for the Cnidian Aphrodite. The lamp stands on a flat base; within is an impressed inscription exhorting the purchase of the lamp. Traces of an orange slip remain.

description.value: Bronze lamp: elongated body and long, fluked, round-tipped nozzle. Circular wick-hole. The top is sunken within a rim extending round the body and nozzle. Nozzle-channel between the filling-hole and the wick-hole. The filling-hole is irregularly oval in shape. A crack in the top has been patched with two strips of bronze. At the rear is a double rod-handle, rising from leaf-shaped springs, curving up and forward to join below a leaf, and to separate, together with a central stem, eventually to terminate in an ivy-leaf-shaped handle-ornament. Undefined flat oval resting-surface. A rectangular patch cut from an ancient inscribed bronze plaque has been let into the rear below the handle-springs; it is incised with the letters HK. Other small areas have also been patched, particularly on top. A Greek inscription is pricked into the side of the lamp. On the right side are cut a few letters that are largely illegible, but also appear to give the name Apsalamos. Surface coloration: cleaned to bare metal and painted green before its acquisition by the Museum; the paint is now removed.

description.value: Bronze lamp: elongated carinated body, somewhat asymmetric, tapering to a flaring nozzle-end, with a circular dished area round the circular wick-hole. Raised rim round the filling-hole, with hinge-pieces at the rear holding a scallop-shell-shaped lamp-lid. Ring-handle with a small thumb-stub at the rear, above which is a handle-ornament in the form of a large crucifix. Surface colouration: patchy green, with large areas of iron staining, and lumps of iron corrosion.

description.value: Bronze lamp with a swing-handle: the lamp has an elongated body and a long splayed and fluked nozzle with a rounded tip and a semicircular wick-hole. The sunken upper surface is within a double rim around the body and nozzle. There is a small hole in the tip of the nozzle. The irregular filling-hole is shaped like an ivy-leaf or bunch of grapes, with indications of an incuse stem above; there is a groove in the nozzle-channel. At the rear is a curved handle of semicircular section, terminating in a calyx from which emerges a goose's head. A small hole is pierced in the edge of the calyx, with part of a chain-link remaining. The flat base follows the shape of the lamp. On each side of the lamp is a tapering lug, on which the lamp swings in the handle. The handle consists of a U-shaped stirrup terminating in duck-head loops and engraved with a vine-scroll and ivy-leaves. On one arm of the U is a ring holding a chain and pin. The stirrup is held by a lotus flower, from which extends a long tapering octagonal hook-and-spike with a double collar; below this is a hook with a duck-head terminal.
